<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td>
	     <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%" >
	     <form action="/cgi-bin/mrate.pl" name="f109483345278581">
	     <tr><td id="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top"><a id="sj" href="/db/item.html?item=30412&amp;mid=109483345278581">Stats</a> <a id="fs8" href="/db/item.html?item=30412&amp;mid=109483345278581#post"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." width="17" height="11" /></a>
	     <br clear="all" /><small>Posted @ Fri, Sep 10th 12:24 PM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform"><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=191513"><span id=" ">The Glorious Rendus</span></a><br /><span id="notbold">10 posts<br /><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Default [1.66]</td><td valign=top class="mform" width="100%"><p>One thing I love about all of you who parrot &quot;But all your stats should be maxed by now!&quot; is your failure to realize where those stats come from.<br/><br/>Where do they come from?<br/><br/>Gear.<br/><br/>The more items without wis you get, the more items you have to get WITH wis to make up for it. Add to that debuffs, and the lack of wis on an item CAN negatively impact the desirability of an item. Sure, you may have 450+ unbuffed wis. Now get this. What did your previous item have for wis? Let's say 20. Now you're at 430 unbuffed wis. Now, another one of these no-wis, good-stats items drop.. Let's say THAT slot had 30 wis. Now you're at 400. Oh, another? Let's say that slot had 25 wis, now has 0. 375 wis. Do it again, and you're at, or below, cap. <br/><br/>You do have to look at your wisdom/int when deciding gear upgrades, no matter how far beyond cap you are. A few ill-chosen upgrades without your casting stat, and you're below your cap. One or two items likely wouldn't hurt someone in these zones, but it could.</p>&nbsp;<br /></td></tr>
